00:18:35,121 --> 00:18:37,031
beim Militargericht.

187
00:18:38,671 --> 00:18:42,671
-This is obviously the right place. How are you doing? -Herr Schindler.

188
00:18:46,451 --> 00:18:50,451
Good-bye, Jews.! Good-bye, Jews.!

189
00:18:50,451 --> 00:18:54,631
Good-bye, Jews! Good-bye, Jews!

190
00:18:55,601 --> 00:18:58,451
Good-bye, Jews.!

191
00:18:58,451 --> 00:19:03,371
Good-bye, Jews.! Good-bye, Jews.!

192
00:19:21,401 --> 00:19:25,171
Oh, my God.

193
00:19:25,171 --> 00:19:28,851
Oy, God. Oh, my God.

194
00:19:35,091 --> 00:19:38,091
Oh, my God.

195
00:19:44,151 --> 00:19:46,031
It could not be better.

196
00:19:46,161 --> 00:19:47,971
-It could be worse. -How? Tell me.

197
00:19:49,531 --> 00:19:53,061
How on earth could it possibly be worse?

198
00:20:06,801 --> 00:20:10,931
-Hey, Goldberg. -Poldek.

199
00:20:10,931 --> 00:20:13,041
-What's this? -Uh, the Judenrat has its own police now.

200
00:20:13,041 --> 00:20:14,851
-You don't say. -Ordnungsdienst.

201
00:20:15,441 --> 00:20:18,331
I'm a policeman now, could you believe it? It's hard to believe.

202
00:20:18,331 --> 00:20:20,241
Oh, no, it's not hard to believe.

203
00:20:20,241 --> 00:20:22,451
It's a good racket, Poldek. The only racket here.

204
00:20:22,451 --> 00:20:25,901
Look, maybe I could put in a good word for you with my superiors.

205
00:20:25,901 --> 00:20:27,261
Your superiors?

206
00:20:27,261 --> 00:20:29,601
Come on, they are not as bad as everyone says.

207
00:20:30,231 --> 00:20:34,051
Well, they're worse than everyone says, but it's a lot of money.

208
00:20:34,241 --> 00:20:35,791
A lot of money.

209
00:20:35,791 --> 00:20:38,191
Give me my housing assignment.

210
00:20:40,021 --> 00:20:42,391
You look funny in that hat, Goldberg.

211
00:20:43,471 --> 00:20:45,671
You look like a clown, you know?

212
00:20:51,921 --> 00:20:54,991
He's a very important man. Just give him two minutes of your time.

213
00:20:54,991 --> 00:20:57,201
Since when did time cost money? Just sit down and listen.

214
00:20:57,201 --> 00:20:59,981
Please. Sir?

215
00:21:04,011 --> 00:21:06,331
For each thousand you invest, I will repay you with...

216
00:21:06,331 --> 00:21:08,801
Two hundred. 200 kilos of enamelware a month

217
00:21:08,801 --> 00:21:10,161
to begin in July and to continue for one year.

218
00:21:10,161 --> 00:21:14,001
After which time, we're even. That's it. It's very simple.

219
00:21:14,001 --> 00:21:16,291
-Not good enough. -It's not good enough.

220
00:21:16,691 --> 00:21:18,861
Not good enough?

221
00:21:18,991 --> 00:21:21,561
Look where you're living. Look where you've been put.

222
00:21:21,561 --> 00:21:22,831
"Not good enough."

223
00:21:22,831 --> 00:21:25,481
A couple of months ago you'd be right, not anymore.

224
00:21:25,621 --> 00:21:28,011
Money's still money.

225
00:21:30,321 --> 00:21:34,161
No, it is not. That's why we're here.

226
00:21:34,161 --> 00:21:38,001
Trade goods that's the only currency that'll be worth anything in the ghetto.

227
00:21:38,001 --> 00:21:40,361
Things have changed, my friend.

228
00:21:42,611 --> 00:21:44,781
Did I call this meeting?

229
00:21:45,111 --> 00:21:47,111
You told Mr. Stern you wanted to speak to me.

230
00:21:47,111 --> 00:21:48,941
I'm here. I've made you a fair offer.

231
00:21:49,141 --> 00:21:51,061
Fair would be a percentage in the company.

232
00:21:51,061 --> 00:21:53,611
Forget the whole thing.

233
00:21:55,281 --> 00:21:57,961
Get out.

234
00:22:02,961 --> 00:22:05,811
How do we know that you will do what you say?

235
00:22:05,841 --> 00:22:09,681
Because I said I would. You want a contract? To be upheld by what court?

236
00:22:09,681 --> 00:22:12,261
I said what I'll do. That's our contract.

237
00:22:49,041 --> 00:22:53,221
The standard SS rate forJewish skilled laborers is seven marks a day...

238
00:22:53,361 --> 00:22:55,641
five for unskilled and women.

239
00:22:56,151 --> 00:22:59,311
This is what you pay the Reich Economic Office.

240
00:22:59,311 --> 00:23:01,771
TheJews themselves receive nothing.

241
00:23:02,101 --> 00:23:06,201
Poles you pay wages. Generally, they get a little more.

242
00:23:06,221 --> 00:23:07,381
-Are you listening? -What was that about the SS?

243
00:23:07,381 --> 00:23:10,731
The rate? The what?

244
00:23:10,731 --> 00:23:12,851
TheJewish worker's salary you pay it directly to the SS, not to the worker.

245
00:23:12,851 --> 00:23:15,351
He gets nothing. -But it's less.

246
00:23:15,351 --> 00:23:18,111
It's less than what I would pay a Pole. -It's less.

247
00:23:18,511 --> 00:23:20,971
That's the point I'm trying to make.

248
00:23:21,591 --> 00:23:23,371
Poles cost more.

249
00:23:24,851 --> 00:23:27,331
Why should I hire Poles?

250
00:23:28,211 --> 00:23:32,241
An enamelware factory over at, uh, Lipowa Street.

251
00:23:32,241 --> 00:23:35,891
It, uh, it, um... It's owned by a German.

252
00:23:35,891 --> 00:23:37,901
But it's outside the ghetto, so you can barter for extra goods...

253
00:23:37,901 --> 00:23:39,931
for eggs, I don't know what you need with the Polish workers.

254
00:23:39,931 --> 00:23:42,321
You can't get it here.

255
00:23:42,321 --> 00:23:45,731
Also, he's asking for ten healthy women for the...

256
00:23:45,731 --> 00:23:47,591
-I am healthy.

257
00:23:47,981 --> 00:23:50,001
Bring your sister, okay?

258
00:23:56,141 --> 00:23:57,711
You need to convince them you have a trade

259
00:23:57,711 --> 00:23:59,321
something valuable to the war effort.

260
00:23:59,321 --> 00:24:00,161
Like what?  What if you don't?

261
00:24:00,161 --> 00:24:01,041
I'm a musician.

262
00:24:01,041 --> 00:24:02,581
Your name goes on a list.

263
00:24:02,581 --> 00:24:05,171
And they put you on trucks...

264
00:24:05,171 --> 00:24:06,121
No, no, no, that's not true.

265
00:24:06,121 --> 00:24:07,541
You're a musician?

266
00:24:07,851 --> 00:24:09,881
-Yeah. -I'd find a good hiding place if I were you.

267
00:24:09,881 --> 00:24:12,081
I'm not going to hide like some animal.

268
00:24:12,081 --> 00:24:14,091
There are places to hide.

269
00:24:20,441 --> 00:24:23,001
I'm a graduate of the University of Lwow.

270
00:24:23,981 --> 00:24:26,671
I used to work at the hydroelectric station in Roznow...

271
00:24:26,671 --> 00:24:28,301
Blauschein.

272
00:24:32,051 --> 00:24:35,791
I'm gonna get the necessary papers because this card is no good anymore.

273
00:24:35,791 --> 00:24:40,011
You can stay in this line all day, you'll still get one of these.

274
00:24:40,111 --> 00:24:44,241
They are no good. You'll have to leave the line now then you'll get a blue card

275
00:24:44,241 --> 00:24:46,351
a Blauschein, to say that you are an essential worker.

276
00:24:46,351 --> 00:24:49,321
I'll get these papers for you at Pankiewicz.

277
00:24:49,711 --> 00:24:51,431
Pharmacist. Just there, look.

278
00:24:51,921 --> 00:24:53,711
Guess who is here?

279
00:24:54,611 --> 00:24:56,011
Poldek! Enjoying the weather, Poldek?

280
00:24:56,011 --> 00:24:57,301
Enjoying the lines?

281
00:24:57,301 --> 00:24:58,641
Need some shoe polish?

282
00:24:58,641 --> 00:25:00,531
In a metal container maybe?

283
00:25:01,331 --> 00:25:05,931
Not essential? I think you misunderstand the meaning of the word.

284
00:25:05,931 --> 00:25:10,151
No Blauschein, sir. Stand over there.  Move. Next!

285
00:25:11,601 --> 00:25:13,591
What do you mean, "Not essential"?

286
00:25:14,481 --> 00:25:19,271
I teach history and literature. Since when it's not essential?

287
00:25:24,361 --> 00:25:26,081
He's a metal polisher.

288
00:25:33,201 --> 00:25:34,351
-It was not right? -It's very good.

289
00:25:34,351 --> 00:25:37,421
He's 53 years old. It's too new.

290
00:25:46,641 --> 00:25:48,941
You're crazy. You left it in your drawer.

291
00:25:48,941 --> 00:25:51,141
How many times have I told you?

292
00:25:51,151 --> 00:25:54,411
Your work certificate you keep in your pocket at all times.

293
00:25:55,081 --> 00:25:55,761
And you leave everything in your drawer.

294
00:25:55,761 --> 00:25:57,841
How many times I've told you?

295
00:25:59,021 --> 00:26:01,121
I'm a metal polisher.

296
00:26:09,781 --> 00:26:12,621
Take the round sheet of tin...

297
00:26:13,141 --> 00:26:15,911
dip it in soap emulsion.

298
00:26:16,951 --> 00:26:20,731
Then place it centrally in the press.

299
00:26:35,601 --> 00:26:39,281
We obtain the soup pot. The soup pot.

300
00:26:39,441 --> 00:26:41,161
Soup pot.

301
00:26:42,711 --> 00:26:45,191
Grosz, Mrs. Grosz, stay together.

302
00:26:49,221 --> 00:26:54,421
Sir, I have ten work permits here for the Deutsche Emailwarenfabrik...

303
00:26:54,421 --> 00:26:57,391
cosigned by Mr. Bankier and myself.

304
00:26:57,391 --> 00:27:01,691
If it's carbonized, clean it with a file.

305
00:27:02,361 --> 00:27:06,721
But don't touch both the electrodes at the same time.

306
00:27:06,721 --> 00:27:09,881
You'll get electrocuted. Here, have a try.

307
00:27:13,621 --> 00:27:16,081
Roll the metal under the press...

308
00:27:16,111 --> 00:27:18,801
but be very careful unless you want your fingers...

309
00:27:18,801 --> 00:27:20,961
to become part of the teapot.

310
00:27:22,741 --> 00:27:23,911
Occupation?

311
00:27:23,911 --> 00:27:26,291
I'm a writer. I play the flute.

312
00:27:26,291 --> 00:27:29,931
But Moses is a skilled metalworker.

313
00:27:29,931 --> 00:27:32,141
He can make tin pots. He can make tanks.

314
00:27:32,141 --> 00:27:34,161
He can make whatever Mr. Schindler asks.

315
00:27:34,161 --> 00:27:35,021
He's highly skilled. Give him your card.

316
00:27:35,021 --> 00:27:38,181
Moses, give him your card.

317
00:27:40,691 --> 00:27:45,091
Now, dip the basin with the tongs into the enamel solution.

318
00:27:47,311 --> 00:27:51,631
And after swiveling it around, carefully place it aside to drip-dry.

319
00:27:54,421 --> 00:27:58,161
And whatever he asks you, allow me just to represent you and speak for you.

320
00:27:58,161 --> 00:28:00,181
Don't say a word.

321
00:28:00,181 --> 00:28:02,471
Filing, billing

322
00:28:02,471 --> 00:28:04,881
keeping track of my appointments, shorthand. Typing, obviously.

323
00:28:04,881 --> 00:28:06,611
How is your typing?

324
00:28:06,611 --> 00:28:07,661
Uh, all right.

325
00:28:07,661 --> 00:28:08,991
Please.

326
00:29:00,371 --> 00:29:02,831
You need a secretary. Pick one.

327
00:29:04,211 --> 00:29:06,521
I don't know how.

328
00:29:06,521 --> 00:29:08,301
They're all so qualified.

329
00:29:08,821 --> 00:29:10,541
You have to choose.

330
00:29:14,001 --> 00:29:16,291
Big smile. Big smile.

331
00:29:38,001 --> 00:29:39,921
If you would, look after my guest.

332
00:29:39,921 --> 00:29:44,131
Um, boxed teas are good. Coffee, pate, um...

333
00:29:44,341 --> 00:29:47,941
-kielbasa sausage, cheeses, Beluga caviar. -Yes.

334
00:29:48,561 --> 00:29:50,471
And, of course, who could live without German cigarettes?

335
00:29:50,471 --> 00:29:51,721
Get me as many as you can find.

336
00:29:52,781 --> 00:29:54,481
And some more fresh fruit.

337
00:29:54,521 --> 00:29:57,301
The real rarities... oranges, lemons, pineapples.

338
00:29:57,301 --> 00:30:00,181
-I need several boxes of Cuban cigars. The best. -Yes.

339
00:30:00,181 --> 00:30:01,961
And dark, unsweetened chocolate.

340
00:30:01,961 --> 00:30:03,921
Not in the shape ofladyfingers, the chunk chocolate.

341
00:30:03,921 --> 00:30:06,281
-Yes. -Big as my hand, you sample at wine tastings.

342
00:30:06,801 --> 00:30:09,681
We're going to need lots of cognac.

343
00:30:09,681 --> 00:30:11,971
The best, Hennessy.

344
00:30:12,561 --> 00:30:14,771
Dom perignon champagne. Um, get L 'espadon sardines...

345
00:30:14,771 --> 00:30:18,411
and, oh, try to find nylon stockings.

346
00:30:20,911 --> 00:30:23,511
It is my distinct pleasure to announce...

347
00:30:23,511 --> 00:30:26,671
the fully operational status of Deutsche Email Fabrik...

348
00:30:26,671 --> 00:30:29,621
Patrzjakies szmaty.!

349
00:30:29,841 --> 00:30:34,021
Manufacturers of superior enamelware crockery...

350
00:30:34,261 --> 00:30:39,111
expressly designed and crafted for military use.

351
00:30:39,181 --> 00:30:43,191
Utilizing only the most modern equipment...

352
00:30:43,191 --> 00:30:50,001
D.E.F. 's staff ofhighly skilled and experienced artisans andjourneymen...

353
00:30:50,001 --> 00:30:51,921
deliver a product of unparalleled quality...

354
00:30:51,921 --> 00:30:53,841
enabling me to proffer, with absolute confidence and pride...

355
00:30:53,841 --> 00:30:56,821
a full line of field and kitchenware unsurpassable

356
00:30:56,821 --> 00:30:59,941
in all respects by my competitors.

357
00:31:00,561 --> 00:31:03,591
See attached list and available colors.

358
00:31:04,401 --> 00:31:07,851
Anticipating the enclosed bids will meet with your approval...

359
00:31:07,851 --> 00:31:11,561
Looking forward to a long and mutually prosperous association.

360
00:31:11,701 --> 00:31:16,501
-Look at this. -I extend to you in advance my sincerest gratitude...

361
00:31:16,501 --> 00:31:17,651
and very best regards. Oskar Schindler.

362
00:31:17,651 --> 00:31:21,011
Yeah, I need 700 gross from here for next Thursday.

363
00:31:21,011 --> 00:31:23,791
Nine hundred... No, make it ten for Wednesday.

364
00:31:23,791 --> 00:31:27,811
All this stuff here goes to Madritsch's factory on Tuesday of next week.

365
00:31:42,801 --> 00:31:46,131
My father was fond of saying, "you need three things in life.'

366
00:31:46,301 --> 00:31:48,091
"A good doctor, a forgiving priest...

367
00:31:48,291 --> 00:31:52,511
and a clever accountant.

368
00:31:56,721 --> 00:32:00,181
The first two... I've never had much use for.

369
00:32:00,181 --> 00:32:02,471
But the third...

370
00:32:08,721 --> 00:32:12,261
Just pretend, for Christ's sake.

371
00:32:16,011 --> 00:32:18,031
Is that all?

372
00:32:23,501 --> 00:32:25,771
I'm trying to thank you.

373
00:32:26,961 --> 00:32:30,411
I'm saying I couldn't have done this without you.

374
00:32:33,011 --> 00:32:35,981
The usual thing would be to acknowledge my gratitude.

375
00:32:35,981 --> 00:32:38,271
It would also, by the way, be the courteous thing.

376
00:32:40,881 --> 00:32:42,791
You're welcome.

377
00:32:51,921 --> 00:32:53,731
Get out of here.

378
00:33:06,231 --> 00:33:09,101
Klonowska, who is it?

379
00:33:18,801 --> 00:33:21,571
She's so embarrassed. Look at her.

380
00:33:32,811 --> 00:33:35,121
You know something? You would like her.

381
00:33:35,121 --> 00:33:37,041
-Oskar, please. -What?

382
00:33:37,041 --> 00:33:38,961
-I don't have to like her... just because you do. -You would, though.

383
00:33:38,961 --> 00:33:41,161
It doesn't work that way.

384
00:33:54,751 --> 00:33:56,881
You've done well here.

385
00:33:59,021 --> 00:34:01,321
You look wonderful.

386
00:34:04,401 --> 00:34:06,411
-Be careful of the step, miss.

387
00:34:06,411 --> 00:34:08,611
-Mrs. Schindler, Marek.

388
00:34:20,651 --> 00:34:22,771
It's not a charade, all this?

389
00:34:22,771 --> 00:34:24,521
How could it be a charade?

390
00:34:24,521 --> 00:34:25,621
The clothes, the car, the apartment. -Wait a minute.

391
00:34:25,621 --> 00:34:29,481
-Take a guess how many people are on my payroll.,  -Oskar.

392
00:34:30,641 --> 00:34:33,601
My father, at the height of his success, had 50.

393
00:34:33,601 --> 00:34:35,601
I've got 350.

394
00:34:35,601 --> 00:34:39,971
350 workers on the factory floor, with one purpose.

395
00:34:40,401 --> 00:34:42,131
To make pots and pans?

396
00:34:42,131 --> 00:34:45,301
To make money. For me.

397
00:34:51,801 --> 00:34:54,981
Does anyone ask about me?

398
00:34:56,181 --> 00:34:57,871
Back home? Everybody.

399
00:34:58,061 --> 00:35:00,931
All the time.

400
00:35:06,011 --> 00:35:10,171
They won't soon forget the name Schindler here, I can tell you that.

401
00:35:12,051 --> 00:35:14,961
"Oskar Schindler  " they'll say.

402
00:35:14,961 --> 00:35:17,451
"Everybody remembers him.

403
00:35:19,001 --> 00:35:22,471
"He did something extraordinary.

404
00:35:23,581 --> 00:35:25,951
"He did something no one else did.

405
00:35:28,511 --> 00:35:30,691
"He came here with nothing...

406
00:35:31,251 --> 00:35:32,991
"a suitcase...

407
00:35:33,931 --> 00:35:38,571
"and built a bankrupt company into a major manufactory.

408
00:35:39,921 --> 00:35:42,731
"And left with a steamer trunk...

409
00:35:42,731 --> 00:35:46,151
"Two steamer trunks full of money...

410
00:35:47,641 --> 00:35:50,491
all the riches of the world."

411
00:35:53,551 --> 00:35:57,201
It's comforting to see that nothing's changed.

412
00:35:57,201 --> 00:35:59,171
You're wrong, Emilie.

413
00:36:00,931 --> 00:36:03,141
There's no way I could have known this before

414
00:36:03,141 --> 00:36:05,351
but there was always something missing.

415
00:36:06,141 --> 00:36:09,551
In every business I tried, I can see now, it wasn't me that failed.

416
00:36:09,551 --> 00:36:11,891
Something was missing.

417
00:36:12,901 --> 00:36:17,471
Even if I'd known what it was, there's nothing I could have done about it...

418
00:36:17,951 --> 00:36:20,351
because you can't create this thing.

419
00:36:20,851 --> 00:36:25,511
And it makes all the difference in the world between success and failure.

420
00:36:26,821 --> 00:36:28,471
Luck?

421
00:36:30,581 --> 00:36:32,121
War.

422
00:36:56,151 --> 00:36:58,151
Should I stay?

423
00:37:00,361 --> 00:37:02,391
It's a beautiful city.

424
00:37:04,401 --> 00:37:07,211
I asked you if I should stay.

425
00:37:09,441 --> 00:37:11,201
It's up to you.

426
00:37:15,811 --> 00:37:17,811
Promise me, Oskar, no doorman or maitre d' will ever presume...

427
00:37:17,811 --> 00:37:22,641
I'm anyone other than Mrs. Schindler

428
00:37:22,681 --> 00:37:24,731
and I'll stay.

429
00:37:27,441 --> 00:37:29,211
Good-bye, darling.

430
00:37:45,451 --> 00:37:49,631
I could try to read this or I could eat my lunch while it's still hot.

431
00:37:50,221 --> 00:37:51,451
We're doing well?

432
00:37:51,451 --> 00:37:51,951
Yes.

433
00:37:51,951 --> 00:37:52,921
Better this month than last?

434
00:37:52,921 --> 00:37:53,361
Yes.

435
00:37:53,361 --> 00:37:55,271
Any reason to think next month will be worse?

436
00:37:55,271 --> 00:37:57,211
The war could end.

437
00:38:08,771 --> 00:38:10,781
-What? -There is a machinist outside

438
00:38:10,781 --> 00:38:13,391
who'd like to thank you personally for giving him a job.

439
00:38:13,831 --> 00:38:17,731
Every day he comes. He's very grateful. It'll just take a minute.

440
00:38:24,081 --> 00:38:26,041
Mr. Lowenstein?

441
00:38:32,881 --> 00:38:36,051
I want to thank you, sir...

442
00:38:36,051 --> 00:38:38,481
for giving me the opportunity to work.

443
00:38:38,481 --> 00:38:41,361
You're welcome. I'm sure you're doing a great job.

444
00:38:41,361 --> 00:38:46,071
The SS beat me up. They would have killed me...

445
00:38:46,231 --> 00:38:50,321
but I am essential to the war effort, thanks to you.

446
00:38:50,411 --> 00:38:51,731
That's great.

447
00:38:52,251 --> 00:38:54,711
I work hard for you.

448
00:38:54,711 --> 00:38:55,841
I'm sure you do.

449
00:38:55,841 --> 00:38:58,641
I'll continue to work hard for you.

450
00:38:58,641 --> 00:39:00,561
That's great. Thanks.

451
00:39:00,561 --> 00:39:02,871
-God bless you, sir. -All right.

452
00:39:03,181 --> 00:39:05,631
You are a good man.

453
00:39:08,211 --> 00:39:09,371
He saved my life.

454
00:39:09,371 --> 00:39:10,801
Yes, he did.

455
00:39:11,321 --> 00:39:13,101
-God bless him. -Yeah. Come on.

456
00:39:16,111 --> 00:39:18,311
God bless you.

457
00:39:30,121 --> 00:39:32,861
I'm sorry, Herr Direktor, but you're running very late.

458
00:39:32,861 --> 00:39:36,081
This is for the Obersturmbannfuhrer, sir.

459
00:39:36,081 --> 00:39:38,961
And this is for his niece, Greta. It's her birthday.

460
00:39:38,961 --> 00:39:41,841
-Greta as in Garbo. -By the way, don't ever do that to me again.

461
00:39:41,841 --> 00:39:44,271
Go. Go, go, drive! Don't bow.

462
00:39:44,271 --> 00:39:46,251
Did you happen to notice that that man had one arm?

463
00:39:46,251 --> 00:39:47,971
What? Did he?

464
00:39:51,721 --> 00:39:54,291
What's his use? -Very useful.

465
00:39:56,761 --> 00:39:57,481
How?

466
00:39:57,481 --> 00:39:59,941
Very useful! Success!

467
00:40:32,771 --> 00:40:35,111
We'll be late for work.

468
00:40:47,111 --> 00:40:49,731
you shouldn't think of them as yours, Oskar.

469
00:40:49,731 --> 00:40:52,581
You need to understand that some of the officers here

470
00:40:52,581 --> 00:40:54,211
don't give a damn about production.

471
00:40:54,801 --> 00:40:57,081
To them, it's a matter of, um, national priority...

472
00:40:57,081 --> 00:41:00,941
thatJews be made to shovel snow.

473
00:41:00,941 --> 00:41:05,531
It's got nothing to do with reality, Oskar. You know it and I know it.

474
00:41:05,631 --> 00:41:11,121
Jews shoveling snow. It's got a, um, ritual significance.

475
00:41:13,711 --> 00:41:14,861
Come with me.

476
00:41:14,861 --> 00:41:17,251
I am an essential worker.

477
00:41:17,251 --> 00:41:18,681
Essential worker?

478
00:41:18,681 --> 00:41:19,901
Yes.

479
00:41:22,471 --> 00:41:24,551
I work for Oskar Schindler.

480
00:41:24,551 --> 00:41:25,621
Essential worker for Oskar Schindler.

481
00:41:25,621 --> 00:41:27,691
A one-armed Jew?

482
00:41:27,691 --> 00:41:29,731
Twice as useless! -Yes, yes.

483
00:41:30,051 --> 00:41:33,191
I lost a day of production, Rolf.

484
00:41:33,201 --> 00:41:36,231
I work for Oskar Schindler.

485
00:41:36,801 --> 00:41:40,451
Danka, look at the snow. Look at the snow. Look at the snow!

486
00:41:44,411 --> 00:41:47,761
I lost a worker. I expect to be compensated.

487
00:41:47,761 --> 00:41:50,861
File a grievance with the Economic Office. It's your right.

488
00:41:50,861 --> 00:41:52,201
Would it do any good?

489
00:41:52,201 --> 00:41:53,921
Of course not.

490
00:41:56,241 --> 00:42:00,651
A big shot from the SS Budget and Construction Office came to lunch...

491
00:42:00,651 --> 00:42:04,401
and he told us that to believe theJewish skilled worker had a place...

492
00:42:04,401 --> 00:42:06,121
in Reich economics

493
00:42:06,121 --> 00:42:08,321
was a treasonable idea.

494
00:42:12,161 --> 00:42:15,341
A one-armed machinist, Oskar?

495
00:42:16,351 --> 00:42:18,661
He was a metal press operator.

496
00:42:22,991 --> 00:42:24,831
Quite skilled.

497
00:42:56,041 --> 00:42:57,311
Herr Direktor?  Shit. I don't believe it.

498
00:42:57,311 --> 00:42:59,401
Stern, is that you?

499
00:42:59,601 --> 00:43:03,511
No, it's Poldek. It's about Stern.

500
00:43:04,241 --> 00:43:07,481
Leave your luggage on the platform.

501
00:43:07,481 --> 00:43:09,781
Clearly label it.

502
00:43:09,801 --> 00:43:13,341
Given name first, then your surname.

503
00:43:13,341 --> 00:43:18,561
Do not bring your baggage with you. It will follow you later.

504
00:43:19,031 --> 00:43:22,621
Leave your luggage on the platform.

505
00:43:22,641 --> 00:43:24,861
Clearly label it.

506
00:43:28,771 --> 00:43:30,211
Stern?

507
00:43:32,921 --> 00:43:34,341
He's on the list.

508
00:43:34,341 --> 00:43:35,691
He is?

509
00:43:35,841 --> 00:43:37,461
Well, let's find him.

